            "id": "424cb4a1970843838c0ab",
            "questionText": "A radio station broadcasts at a frequency of $!$98.5 \\ MHz$!$. The electromagnetic waves travel from the transmitter to a receiver located $!$100 \\ km$!$ away. Due to atmospheric conditions, the signal experiences a slight delay of $!$0.0001 \\ s$!$. Given that electromagnetic waves are produced by accelerating charges, calculate the phase difference between the emitted signal and the received signal. (Use the speed of light as $!$3.00 \\times 10^8 \\ m/s$!$).",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "419d3ee74fe844b2bcee1",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that relates the phase difference to the frequency and the time delay. Choose the correct expression for calculating phase difference between two signals when there is a time delay.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0c3ff372-9bd8-4961-9294-ab325dbdc20e",
                        "ee8bb1a6-fd07-4f51-81ae-e388a2828537"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\phi = 2\\pi f \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\phi = \\frac{\\Delta t}{2\\pi f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
